      "body" : "What if the String <b>notes</b> contains a <code>%</code> character?"
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 51705,
        "reputation" : 21826,
        "user_id" : 154527,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 100,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9367d0448b8fc3e6d7f6cd421940ac62?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Alain O&#39;Dea",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/154527/alain-odea"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1450907963,
      "post_id" : 8248052,
      "comment_id" : 56630513,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "This is vulnerable to trivial SQL injection attacks.  They may only broaden the scope of returned values but could easily DoS the database by stuffing piles of <code>%this%that%theother%</code> into the query making it very heavy to service.  Adding <code>ESCAPE &#39;!&#39;</code> to the query and running <code>notes = notes.replace(&quot;!&quot;, &quot;!!&quot;).replace(&quot;_&quot;, &quot;!_&quot;).replace(&quot;[&quot;, &quot;![&quot;)</code> prior to supplying <b>notes</b> as a parameter improves things.  Using a full text query mechanism which handles these intricacies directly for you is best."
    }, {
